UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1231
1 A JOINT RESOLUTION designating the Jean Ritchie Memorial Highway in Perry
2 County.
3 WHEREAS, Jean Ruth Ritchie was born to Abigail Hall Ritchie and Balis Ritchie
4 on December 8, 1922, in Viper, Kentucky, the youngest of fourteen children; and
5 WHEREAS, Jean Ritchie was a curious child and spent her childhood learning
6 traditional songs from her parents and other relatives; and
7 WHEREAS, the Ritchie family was known for their love of traditional folk music
8 passed down for generations, and were a major repository of Appalachian Mountain
9 songs and traditions for folk music scholars, as detailed in Jean Ritchie's 1955 book titled
10 Singing Family of the Cumberlands; and
11 WHEREAS, Jean Ritchie attended Perry County High School and Cumberland
12 College, before graduating from the University of Kentucky in 1946 with a degree in
13 social work; and
14 WHEREAS, Jean Ritchie moved to New York City after graduation to become a
15 social worker at the Henry Street Settlement in the Lower East Side; and
16 WHEREAS, in 1950, Jean Ritchie married photographer George Pickow, with
17 whom she had two sons, Peter and Jonathan, both of whom would later perform and sing
18 with her; and
19 WHEREAS, by 1951, Jean Ritchie changed careers to become a full-time singer,
20 folk song collector, and songwriter; and
21 WHEREAS, while living in New York City, Jean Ritchie befriended many popular
22 folk musicians of the day, including Woody Guthrie, Oscar Brand, and Pete Seeger. Jean
23 Ritchie also met Alan Lomax, a noted American ethnomusicologist and folk music
24 historian, who recorded her extensively for the Library of Congress in 1951; and
25 WHEREAS, in 1952, Jean Ritchie released her first solo album of family songs and
26 was awarded a Fulbright scholarship to travel around Scotland and Ireland to study the
27 origins of the songs her family held dear in Appalachia; and
