UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1231
1 WHEREAS, Jean Ritchie published several books throughout her career, including
2 A Garland of Mountain Song, The Dulcimer Book, Jean Ritchie's Swapping Song Book,
3 Folk Songs of the Southern Appalachians, and Jean Ritchie's Dulcimer People; and
4 WHEREAS, Jean Ritchie performed at the first Newport Folk Festival in 1959, and
5 the burgeoning folk music revival of the day continued to grow into the 1960s, when folk
6 music became a major force in popular American music; and
7 WHEREAS, in 1977, Jean Ritchie's album None but One won the critics' award in
8 the Rolling Stone magazine; and
9 WHEREAS, Jean Ritchie was crucial to the popularity in the United States of the
10 mountain dulcimer, the instrument her family traditionally played with a goose feather,
11 and was the reason many were introduced to it. The dulcimer became so popular that Jean
12 Ritchie released an album titled The Most Dulcimer in 1984; and
13 WHEREAS, in 1996, a documentary film, Mountain Born: The Jean Ritchie Story,
14 was released nationwide and chronicled her life and work with Appalachian folk music;
15 and
16 WHEREAS, in 2002, Jean Ritchie received a National Heritage Fellowship from
17 the National Endowment for the Arts and was also inducted into the Kentucky Music
18 Hall of Fame; and
19 WHEREAS, Jean Ritchie left these earthly bounds on June 1, 2015, at her home in
20 Berea, Kentucky; and
21 WHEREAS, Jean Ritchie's impact on folk music continues to this day and her
22 enduring love of her family's music, home state of Kentucky, and the mountain dulcimer
23 lives on in those impacted by her music;
24 NOW, THEREFORE,
25 Be it resolved by the General Assembly of the Commonwealth of Kentucky:
26 Section 1. The Transportation Cabinet shall designate a portion of Kentucky
27 Route 7 in Perry County, from mile point 1 to mile point 7, as the "Jean Ritchie Memorial
Page 2 of 3
